If #VladimirPutin chose to test this resolve, perhaps with a 'minor' incursion into the #Balticregion, how would President Trump 2.0 respond: with military force, or with a phone call to the #Kremlin? We do not know.  But we do know that Europe will have little to say about this. But at least for the next decade, the Europeans will not have the power to repel a #Russianattack.  Everything, as always, depends on the #Americans. The big question is 'Why?' The European allies do not lack people or money. Their population is 590 million (the United States is 330 million). Their combined #GDP is about $18 trillion (the United States, $26 trillion). One reason for this inaction is the political process: in peacetime, voters generally prefer #welfarespending.  Another, more sophisticated reason is that decision makers and opinion makers believe that the United States needs allies and is, therefore, willing to pay for its security. The war in #Ukraine showed the limits to American risk appetite in that area.  The US faces an existential challenge with #China. Imagine if Europe had begun to take internal and external security seriously after one of the many alarm bells long ignored in the past, such as Russia's cyber attack on #Estonia in 2007.  At this point, the Europeans could be a formidable global partner for the United States, not only on China but also on other pressing global issues.  This would mean costs and responsibilities.  But it would also bring privileges, not least being taken seriously!  $URL[0]

At this meeting with the Americans, Ukraine proposed three key points: silence in the skiesâ€”stopping missile strikes, bombs, and long-range drone attacks; silence at sea; real confidence-building measures in this whole situation, in which diplomacy is ongoing, which primarily means the release of prisoners of war and detaineesâ€”both military and civilianâ€”and the return of Ukrainian children who were forcibly transferred to Russia.  The American side understands our arguments and considers our proposals. I am grateful to President Trump for the constructive conversation between our teams.  During todayâ€™s talks, the U.S. side proposed taking an even bigger first stepâ€”a 30-day full interim ceasefire, not only stopping missile, drone, and bomb attacks, not only in the Black Sea, but also along the entire front line.  Ukraine is ready to accept this proposalâ€”we see it as a positive step and are ready to take it. Now, it is up to the United States to convince Russia to do the same. If Russia agrees, the ceasefire will take effect immediately.

RT @ipacglobal: **IPAC STATEMENT ON THE DEPORTATION OF UYGHURS FROM THAILAND TO CHINA**  We, the members of the Inter-Parliamentary Alliance on China (IPAC), abhor the Thai governmentâ€™s refoulement of 40 Uyghur men to China. This action constitutes a flagrant violation of Thailandâ€™s obligations under international law, including the fundamental principle of non-refoulement which Thailand is bound to.  The Uyghurs in question fled persecution and discrimination in the Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region (XUAR), seeking safety through Thailand. Instead, they were subjected to up to 12 years of indefinite detention in life-threatening conditions, during which five people died, which UN experts noted may amount to torture and arbitrary detention.  The Thai government also ignored its own national 'Anti-torture law' which prohibits non-refoulement, and overwhelming evidence and multiple warnings from UN experts and human rights organisations - including Thailandâ€™s own National Human Rights Commission - that these individuals would face torture, persecution, imprisonment, or worse.  It was unambiguous that the group of Uyghur were seeking international protection, with 48 men from the original group of Uyghur submitting asylum applications to the UNHCR. Additionally, despite clear indications that foreign governments were willing to resettle these men, providing a safe alternative to refoulement, the Thai authorities proceeded with their forced return.  As a member of the United Nations Human Rights Council, the Thai government has a firm responsibility to uphold human rights. By deporting the group of Uyghur to China, in full knowledge of the grave risks they face, the Thai government has severely damaged global credibility and undermined its bilateral and multilateral relationships.  As IPAC, we commit ourselves to press for our respective governments to advocate for the urgent release of these men, and to hold accountable those who have violated their fundamental rights.

Estimating Excess Deaths in China from Covid Lockdowns and Covid Infections         There have been various attempts to estimate the mortality numbers for China with the end of the zero-Covid policy, which resulted in a surge of infections and hospitalizations. Using obituary data from 3 universities and Baidu search as a proxy for all regions, Xiao, Wang, and Liu, et al (2023) provided a guesstimate that â€œan estimated 1.87 million excess deaths occurred among individuals 30 years and older during the first 2 months after the end of Chinaâ€™s zero COVID policy.â€  We now have the mortality data from Chinaâ€™s National Bureau of Statistics, which show that the mortality rate for China jumped in the years of 2021-2023. Using the mortality rates, we can make a quick estimate of the number of excess deaths for each year. The deaths could be from Covid-19 infections, but they could also be from the implementation of zero-Covid restrictions.        Chinaâ€™s mortality rate was at 7.09 per thousand in 2019 and 7.87 per thousand in 2023. By simple arithmetic and factoring in Chinaâ€™s 1.41 billion population size, the difference between 2023 and 2019 was 1.1 million, which would be a rough measure of the number of excess deaths for 2023.   Using as the base the average mortality rate for period 2015-2019 (7.068 per 1,000 people) and the national population figures for each year, the excess deaths for 2020-2023 are calculated as follows:  2020:   2,824 (While Wuhan/Hubei suffered, the rest of the country benefited from the zero-Covid policies and had fewer deaths). 2021: 158,211 2022: 426,348 2023: 1,130,555 Conclusion: Based on official population statistics, the total number of excess deaths for the period 2020-2023 is approximately 1,717,939. These numbers are subject to revisions when the population census becomes available and I look forward to the estimates by demographers.

#chinacanadaties On September 25, the Chinese Embassy in Canada hosted a reception celebrating the 75th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China (PRC). Around 500 guests from the Canadian government, the parliament and all walks of life, including the Honourable Senator Paul Massicotte, Yuen Pau Woo, Jean-Guy Dagenais, the Honourable Former Senator Victor Oh, Member of Parliament Mr. Majid Jowhari, Mr. Paul Chiang, Mr. Chandra Arya and Ms. Niki Ashton, Assistant Deputy Minister of Global Affairs Canada Weldon Epp, Assistant Deputy Minister of Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada Kathleen Donohue, Canadian Ambassador to China Her Excellency Jennifer May, Former Vice Chief of the Defence Staff Lieutenant General Denis Rouleau, and foreign envoys as well as representatives from Chinese enterprises, local Chinese communities and Chinese overseas students attended the event.  The reception first featured a video clip titled 'The PRC: My Story,' introducing the all-around achievements of the PRC over 75 years and her image in Canadian eyes. His Excellency Wang Di, Chinese Ambassador to Canada, highlighted the spirit of the 3rd Plenary Session of the 20th Central Committee of the Communist Party of China and emphasized China's willingness to deepen exchanges and cooperation with the Canadian side in various areas with a positive, pragmatic and constructive attitude, to welcome the 55th anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic relations between the two countries and the 20th anniversary of the establishment of the strategic partnership next year.  In his speech, the Honourable Former Senator Victor Oh spoke highly of China's development and achievements, referring to China as 'a country with a bright future' and emphasizing the long history of China-Canada friendship. He pointed out that with mutual respect and understanding, the two countries will move forward to building a closer and more cooperative relationship.  In a warm and friendly atmosphere, the guests watched a thematic photo exhibition and brilliant cultural performances, highly appreciating China's development and achievements while speaking positively about China-Canada relations.

Just back from 3 days in DC. 30k foot observations:  1) Early on the week the macro community was preoccupied making fun of @realDonaldTrump trade policy reversals rather than focusing on the evident â€œselfâ€ de-escalation norm since April 2nd  2) The lack of a cohesive execution strategy and intellectually honest set of goals behind trade policy, created a fog of war, which distracted pretty much everyone from the fact that President Trump has been reacting to feedback on the economy and market performance since April 9th. I found most macro analyst were trying to make logical sense of bygones rather than taking a leap of faith that the actions taken post liberation day were genuine recalibration / de-escalation from the self-defeating tariff actions  3) The bearish arguments from market participants were numerous, but I found that most of them can be attributed to fog of war. One argument of the bears is the idea that SPX valuation is high for a recessionary environment, with many pointing out 15 PE x 250 EPS = 3,750 as recessionary fair value. While I donâ€™t dispute the idea that SPX valuation would de-rate if we fall into a recessionary regime, I think that over emphasizing this argument is premature and out of touch with the recent direction of travel, i.e. Trump actions since April 9th have been consistently pressuring recession odds lower  4) My view of self de-escalation was reinforced by meetings at the White House and with Congress staffers, where I left with an impression that the President is getting a lot of feedback from the economy, tracking market reactions closely, aware of where public opinion stands and importantly that there is a goal to wrap up trade war in the near future so the focus can move to reconciliation. My feedback to a White House staffer was that emphasizing that there is an aspirational ending date to trade policy actions would go a long way in anchoring markets and move the narrative away from â€œUS existential crisisâ€  5) Whether the President continues the sequence of â€œselfâ€ de-escalation from here remains in my mind a close to 50/50 bet. But I think the regime has evolved from where we were post liberation day, as the President is â€œmoving his feetâ€ and risk managing his tariffs actions. Ex-ante, I continue to weight the de-escalation node over the self-destruction node  6) Peter Navarro wasnâ€™t mentioned in any of my meetings in DC. In fact, his last TV appearance was on April 13th, apparently an unauthorized appearance which cost him exclusion from WH senior staff meetings. I hope I didnâ€™t jinx us by highlighting this  7) Lastly, views on how much spending cuts will be included in the reconciliation bill depend on whether you are talking to the House or to the Senate. I left with the vibe that we wonâ€™t see much efforts to cut spending which will keep deficits higher for longer. I hope this feel is proven wrong

The group benefitted from widespread unemployment throughout Gaza and hired thousands of young men for as little as 100 shekels a day to be part of highly compartmentalized digging and excavation operations which produced the hundreds of kilometers of tunnels that Hamas had at its disposal. There were times when people would report hearing strange noises or feeling unusual vibrations underneath their homes due to extensive tunneling activities. In a few instances that I recall being told about, Hamas would dispatch its Internal Security Service (Jihaz al-Amin al-Dakhili) officers to people or businesses who made a fuss about suspected excavation operations underneath their homes and businesses; the group would use the carrot and stick approach to either buy silence or threaten severe consequences for â€œundermining resistance operations.â€ Iâ€™ve even heard of some cases where Hamas would ask some homeowners or families to â€œhostâ€ tunnel entrances that could be later used by the group or its members if needed in exchange for financial incentives.  As for the secret intelligence base underneath UNRWAâ€™s headquarters, it is difficult to imagine such a massively complicated subterranean structure being constructed without someone, somewhere, noticing unusual activities. While UNRWA as an organization likely had no idea that this was taking place right under their nose, Hamas must absolutely have had someone on the inside providing the group with observations and information to minimize the risk of detection throughout the construction and operation of the intelligence base. In addition to Hamas penetrating UNRWAâ€™s rank and file, it created a hostile and dangerous environment for UN staff and managers who sought to investigate the groupâ€™s members within the UN agency and the extent of Hamasâ€™s infiltration of the aid organization. As the New York Times reported, a British administrator in UNRWA attempted to investigate agency employees who were affiliated with Hamas in 2014 but received multiple death threats and warnings which resulted in his ultimate departure from the agency. More damagingly, other UNRWA leaders became reluctant to conduct detailed investigations of Hamas, compromising the UN agency. The IDF showed a group of reporters a cluster of wires going from UNRWAâ€™s own database center down below ground to allegedly show a direct connection with Hamasâ€™s subterranean intelligence base; this may be difficult to verify or explain but it is not beyond the realm of possibilities that Hamasâ€™s intelligence operatives may have compromised UNRWAâ€™s IT staff and computer network administrators.  This is yet another scandal that shows the shameful extent to which Hamas victimized its own people and even organizations seeking to do good in Gaza, all in pursuit of supposed acts of resistance against the Israeli occupation and injustices. Ironically, and despite the incredibly helpful and highly necessary work that UNRWA does, the agency ultimately enabled Hamas to outsource its government responsibilities to provide for Gazans, and in return, was used as a shield by the terror group. Furthermore, and at a time when Gazaâ€™s population was largely aid-dependent and suffering from unemployment and a grim future, Hamas spent hundreds of millions, possibly a few billion dollars over 17 years, to build tunnels and terror infrastructure. Remember what I said about Hamasâ€™s intelligence and counterintelligence capabilities being used to repress Gazans and combat any opposition to the groupâ€™s iron grip over the coastal enclave. RT @TapoBhat: Many activities during physical robotic caregiving require a robot to come in contact with a human not just at the end-effector but over the entire robot arm including the joints. For a robot to sense and perceive these contact events and leverage them for whole-arm manipulation, we need whole-arm robot skins that not only cover the entire robot arm but are also perceived to be comfortable to touch by the humans they are touching. Softness of the skin with high resolution coverage over robot links and joints using stretchability as robot arms move is our key. Our whole-arm robot skin paper develops CushSense, a soft and stretchable whole-arm robot skin for physical human-robot interaction using a capacitive sensing technology that people perceive to be comfortable to touch. Compliance in the hardware can go a long way to augment software compliance for low-level safety. The entire hardware design is open source and you can build your own CushSense! After nearly six years of research and fieldwork (delayed by the COVID pandemic), my study â€œRed Tide: CCP Propaganda and United Front in the 21st Century Case Studies in Japan, Singapore, South Korea, Hong Kong, and Taiwanâ€ is finally ready for release in January 2025. The full report runs over 100 pages and 35,000 wordsâ€”a soft release of the executive summary is forthcoming shortly.   The study provides a detailed examination of how the Chinese Communist Partyâ€™s strict ideological controls that it exerted internally through propaganda and united front to maintain political control are now being projected outward by political warfare aimed at both protecting CCP rule and undermining its political adversaries. Contrary to the perception that the CCPâ€™s united front is singularly focused on Taiwan, CCP propaganda and united front activities in the five case studies in this study demonstrate an expansive remit that underscores the Party-stateâ€™s global ambitions.   Prior understanding of the Central Propaganda Department and the United Front Work Department were often too compartmentalized, and treated the two organs as siloed systems, leading to their net effects being underappreciated. While functionally different bureaucracies, CPD and UFWD are increasingly operationally integratedâ€”together with intelligence functions. General Secretary Xi Jinping has institutionalized the convergence of the propaganda and united front systems through multiple central leading small groups into a system of systems approach for political warfare in the 21st century.   This study provides case studies of how the CCP uses these tools for political warfare in Hong Kong, Japan, Singapore, South Korea, and Taiwan.

My husband's aunt comes over a few times a week and spends time with the kids. She's been helping me reorganize cupboards, bringing over bins, lining my drawers with little cute mats, and I've felt guilty because my mind says 'this should have been done already.'  Moments ago she said, 'I'm glad this makes you happy. My mother used to do this type of stuff for me.'   And now I'm emotional realizing that she's not helping because she judges me for some disorganized cupboards, thinks I'm incapable of this task, or whatever else I may tell myself.  She's helping me because she just wants to. She knows how much time it saves me so I can focus on other things. Her mother helped her, now she helps me. A passing of the generational torch, if you will.  We've lost this collectively and we need to bring it back. Generational support makes a huge difference, and if we don't have that support ourselves, we MUST be prepared to provide that for our own children or family members when the time comes.   Be the change.  Thanks for coming to my Ted Talk.

In 2016 I hated Trump so much.   I hysterically cried on election night. I sobbed and screamed about how he would 'take away our rights' and 'destroy our country'. I screamed how everyone who voted for him was an 'ist' of some kind.   And over the following 3 years my world was turned upside down. I started listening to the 'other side'. I started genuinely trying to understand. I read and listened far more than I spoke. I stopped lashing out at people.  And then I saw it. I finally stood back and stopped screaming long enough to see how much hatred had built up in my own heart. How contradictory the ideas I held were. I finally started uncovering the lies.  I spent a lot of time thinking. Weeding through the mess inside my head. My opinions started to shift and change.   Looking back, it seems like it happened slowly and then all at once.   In 2019, I left the Left. In 2020 I voted for Trump. In 2024 I found God.  I've been called a liar. A grifter. Brainwashed. A 'pick-me'. Any insult you can think of, I've probably seen it floating around my comment sections.  The reality is: I changed. A lot. And there's more stories like mine. Share yours if you have one, I'd love to read them. ğŸ’œ

The success of his work, in partnership with the bold and positive vision of the Emirati government, has been a shining light in the world and a strong counter to the history of division.  Before World War 2, Jews and Muslims lived together throughout the Middle East in harmony for many centuries, celebrating their shared values, and the UAE is leading us back to that time.  In the UAE, people of all faiths and backgrounds thrive together in an environment of mutual understanding and respect. Ivanka and I will be donating $1 million to the Chabad of UAE and will redouble our efforts to work with the Jewish community and the countryâ€™s leadership to build a resilient, vibrant Jewish community in Abu Dhabi and Dubai. We welcome others to join us in this effort.  The constant scapegoating of Israel and the Jewish people benefits no one, other than inept leaders who use hatred to deflect from their own shortcomings. Itâ€™s time for the world to channel its collective energy to uplift our shared goals and ambitions.  To all who wish to aggravate these historic divides, know that your efforts only strengthen the resolve of the Jewish community to contribute to societies that respect and welcome us. History has shown that those who embrace the Jewish people benefit, and those who persecute the Jewish people ultimately face spectacular defeat.  Let us come together from all faiths to pick up where Rabbi Kogan left off and bring his work, and the work of those building the UAE into a thriving destination of tolerance, bridge building and mutual benefit, to new heights.
